ElliEz00.name: Ezekiel Elliott
ElliEz00.note: Elliott will be suspended for the first six games of the NFL season under the personal conduct policy. He is expected to appeal.

FreeDe01.name: Devonta Freeman
FreeDe01.note: Atlanta Falcons RB Devonta Freeman (concussion) was out of practice Monday, Aug. 14, and he is in the concussion protocol. He has been ruled out for the second preseason game.

AjayJa00.name: Jay Ajayi
AjayJa00.note: Miami Dolphins RB Jay Ajayi suffered a concussion in practice on July 31. UPDATE: On August 13th, Ajayi is no longer in the concussion protocol, according to head coach Adam Gase.

LyncMa00.name: Marshawn Lynch
LyncMa00.note: Lynch works as a best ball play because best ball rosters usually offer enough bench space to hedge early pick collapse/injury. If Lynch simply reproduces what Latavius Murray did last year, he would be worth more than his ADP. Savvy best ball drafters can get a high weekly floor/low ceiling receiving back option or two to gird against the possibility that Lynch has nothing left in the tank to earn the reward of having a second RB1 or waiting on RB1 and not getting hurt.

FourLe00.name: Leonard Fournette
FourLe00.note: Fournette has a foot injury and will miss the second preseason game. The team intends to be "careful" with him.

CrowIs01.name: Isaiah Crowell
CrowIs01.note: Did you know Crowell was a double-digit PPR scorer in nine of 15 weeks through Week 16 last year? And that five of those nine were over 15 points, three over 20? Add in upgrades on the offensive line and a quarterback situation that could have some modest improvements and Crowell looks like a quality foundation best ball back that you can get in the fourth round.

MontTy01.name: Ty Montgomery
MontTy01.note: Montgomery’s weekly outcomes last year spanned a wide range, which could be maddening for typical weekly lineup leagues, but should be just fine for best ball leagues. When the gameplan calls for a lot of Montgomery, he can be among the top two or three running backs in a PPR league, but if one of the rookies or fullback Aaron Ripkowski get more work, Montgomery can be automatically be covered by your running back depth.

CookBr01.name: Brandin Cooks
CookBr01.note: Cooks could be an extremely frustrating player to owner in typical redraft leagues, with the Patriots potentially having as many as 10 or 11 players touch the ball on offense most weeks. In best ball leagues, you’ll get the benefit of Cooks feast weeks when opponents don’t correctly account for his speed while avoiding the cost of famine weeks when he is more of a decoy or neutralized while other players are featured.

PoweBi00.name: Bilal Powell
PoweBi00.note: Powell will have to share the backfield with Matt Forte in an offense going nowhere, but Forte is getting close to the breakdown phase of his career and Powell was a top five running back after Forte went out last year. He also contributed five double-digit PPR scoring weeks before Forte got hurt. At a 6th/7th round cost, Powell provides a floor of a RB2/Flex scoring around half of the time with a sky high ceiling for teams that neglect running back early in best ball drafts.

IngrMa01.name: Mark Ingram
IngrMa01.note: Ingram was going as high as the third round before Adrian Peterson was signed, now he is often going after Peterson. That could look rational by year’s end, but Ingram has always been a player who is motivated by competition, and he has been highly efficient in a great offense for running back fantasy scoring, so his fall in ADP presents a great buying opportunity in best ball leagues.

BryaMa01.name: Martavis Bryant
BryaMa01.note: Bryant carries risk of rust from a year layoff, but he had three top 12 wide receiver weeks in each of 2014 and 2015 despite only playing in 21 games. Bryant gives your best ball lineup a higher weekly ceiling at the cost of a 5th/6th round pick - which means you can hedge for another suspension or disappointment while still getting the possible benefit of a big play receiver in a big play offense.

PeteAd01.name: Adrian Peterson
PeteAd01.note: Best ball drafts allow us to play with what if questions. What if Adrian Peterson returns to form in one of the most potent fantasy backfields for big weeks (only Arizona and Pittsburgh had more top 10 PPR running back weeks last year). What if Mark Ingram can’t stay healthy or gets traded? If any of these come to pass, Peterson will help make drafts, and if they don’t he’ll still likely contribute a handful of high scores to justify his mid-round price tag.

LuckAn00.name: Andrew Luck
LuckAn00.note: Luck had right shoulder surgery in January 2017 to repair an injury (partially torn labrum) that dated back to the 2015 season. There is no timetable for his return. He has begun camp on the PUP list and could miss the entire preseason. Team owner Robert Irsay has said he will be back "around" the season opener.

WoodDa02.name: Danny Woodhead
WoodDa02.note: Woodhead was an RB1 on average in PPR leagues in 2015, and he’ll get an inflated opportunity in the passing game for the first four contests while Kenneth Dixon is suspended in an offense that loves to target the running back and has a shortage of proven wide receivers. He fits well as part of a best ball draft approach that waits on running back until the mid-rounds.

GoreFr00.name: Frank Gore
GoreFr00.note: Gore is almost certainly going to slow down a bit in 2017, but he was able to score eight times and have 10 double-digit scoring weeks in PPR leagues. Even if those are more sporadic and unpredictable this year, he should deliver enough as the lead back to merit his 8th round cost in best ball leagues if your team went away from running back early.

MartDo00.name: Doug Martin
MartDo00.note: Martin is ideal for best ball leagues even though you’ll miss him for the first three weeks. His backup, jacquizz Rodgers, is very cheap and gives you injury insurance as long as the roster is big enough to justify 5 running back picks. Martin might not live up to his 2015 and offseason hype, but if he does, he’ll give you a chance to win because he is going at a fraction of the price his 2015 RB1 production levels would dictate.

WatkSa00.name: Sammy Watkins
WatkSa00.note: Watkins was a top seven PPR receiver in the second half of 2015 - the last time he was healthy. He has the potential to be the #1 scoring wideout in any given week. His injury history is disturbing, but the depth at wide receiver and ability to take cheap solid scorers late in your draft make Watkins a good “swing for the fences” option in the third round.

WestTe01.name: Terrance West
WestTe01.note: If West simply leads the Ravens in carries and rushing touchdowns again this year, he’ll easily merit the 12th-14th round pick it costs to add him to your later running back picks in best ball leagues. West also should get more work in the first four games with Kenneth Dixon out. Three of them are at home, where three of West’s four biggest fantasy games came last year.

GillMi00.name: Mike Gillislee
GillMi00.note: Don’t expect Gillislee to reproduce LeGarrette Blount’s 18 touchdown 2016 campaign for New England, but do expect him to lead a high-scoring offense in rushing touchdowns. You don’t have to time the starts in a best ball league, so Gillislee makes a lot of sense in the 7th/8th round as part of an approach that ignores running back early.

AbduAm00.name: Ameer Abdullah
AbduAm00.note: Abdullah was terrific in his one full game last year, but it is hard to know what his role would have looked like if he had stayed healthy all year. The team is calling him the starter and the PPR weekly upside even with Theo Riddick in the picture should easily justify his draft price. Depth can cover the downside possibility of a split role while the giving weekly RB1 upside possibilities as a price much cheaper than surer RB1s.

PeriSa00.name: Samaje Perine
PeriSa00.note: Perine works as part of a RB2BC strategy in best ball leagues. His talent is superior to Rob Kelley and he should overtake him at some point this year. Kelley is going later than Perine and 20 man roster best ball leagues offer the space to take both and bank an RB2 in at least 6-8 weeks as long as Washington doesn’t split the work between the two of them.

WillTy00.name: Tyrell Williams
WillTy00.note: It’s almost like Williams didn’t have 1,000 yards in his second season after going undrafted. He will have to hold off #7 overall pick Mike Williams, Keenan Allen’s return will surely lower his season-long and weekly ceiling, and a healthy Travis Benjamin won’t help either. Still, a player with his accomplishments last year (while playing through a shoulder injury in the last third of the season) and quarterback quality is a welcome addition to your best ball roster.

BrowJo01.name: John Brown
BrowJo01.note: Brown has been missing practices in training camp with a quad injury. Head coach Bruce Arians said it was a concern.

MariMa01.name: Marcus Mariota
MariMa01.note: Mariota was held down early and late in the season by the tough Minnesota, Houston, Kansas City, and Denver defenses, but only one of those teams will be on the schedule this year. When in the soft underbelly of opponents last year, Mariota finished in the top five quarterback with scores in the high 20’s or 30’s four times in a six-week midseason stretch, and his wide receivers should be upgraded with the addition of #5 pick Corey Davis and touchdown maker Eric Decker.

ThieAd00.name: Adam Thielen
ThieAd00.note: Thielen traded off big target and scoring weeks with Stefon Diggs, but is going at a fraction of Diggs’ cost in best ball drafts. Between him, Diggs, and a possibly emerging Laquon Treadwell, the wide receiver scoring for the Vikings could be inconsistent, but the best ball format allows you to benefit from Thielen’s inevitable big weeks without suffering the cost of his down weeks.

FortMa00.name: Matt Forte
FortMa00.note: Forte has been missing practices for two weeks with a hamstring issue.

BlouLe00.name: LeGarrette Blount
BlouLe00.note: Blount won’t get 18 rushing touchdowns like he did last year in New England, but it’s not difficult to imagine him equalling or even bettering Ryan Mathews’ eight from last year for the Eagles. If he does that, Blount should contribute at least 5-6 scoring weeks for best ball teams at running back, which is a fine return on the mid-round pick he will cost in drafts.

ReedJo02.name: Jordan Reed
ReedJo02.note: Washington Redskins TE Jordan Reed (toe) was placed on the Physically Unable to Perform list because of significant toe soreness, according to a team spokesperson. He has had a special orthotic placed in his shoe and hinted at a fracture in his foot.

RudoKy00.name: Kyle Rudolph
RudoKy00.note: Rudolph tied Travis Kelce for the most 15+ PPR games last year (7), which is the name of the game in best ball leagues. He’s going at a fraction of Kelce’s price and works as a rock solid TE1 or TE2 who can help you have the best tight end scoring in your best ball league.

JohnDu00.name: Duke Johnson
JohnDu00.note: Johnson won’t win your best ball league, but he might keep you from falling apart if you have a high risk running back group. He only fell below six PPR points twice through Week 16, and he added five double digit scoring weeks along the way. He’s a good fit for best ball drafts that only take two running backs through the first 9-10 rounds.

HenrDe00.name: Derrick Henry
HenrDe00.note: Henry is about as expensive as handcuffs can be in fantasy drafts, but the Titans running game is very productive and he is clearly very talented. He has league winner potential if Demarco Murray goes down.

NewtCa00.name: Cam Newton
NewtCa00.note: Newton won’t be as bad as he was last year when he was struggling with injuries and poor play, and he won’t as good as he was in 2015, when was the clear #1 quarterback. He’ll fall somewhere in between, and as long as he has some big weeks driven by goal line runs and red zone efficiency, he’ll be worth his mid-round price in best ball leagues, where you can pair him with a more consistent quarterback to lessen the pain from his down weeks.

JackDe00.name: DeSean Jackson
JackDe00.note: Jackson has always been one of the prototype best ball picks. He’ll break through with long touchdowns peridiocally and disappear or miss other games because of injury. Having him as your WR3 or WR4 in a best ball format gives the high weekly ceiling while your depth will take the low weekly floor out of play.

EifeTy00.name: Tyler Eifert
EifeTy00.note: Eifert’s durability is highly questionable, but his productivity and high weekly ceiling are not. In his six healthy weeks last year, he finished in the top three tight ends three times and the #1 tight end twice. He’s a worthy TE1 as long as you can draft for the potential of extended absences as he recovers from the back issue that prematurely ended his 2016.

WilsRu00.name: Russell Wilson
WilsRu00.note: Wilson was a dud across all formats while he was hurt last year, but once he was healthy, he delivered the top 3-5 finishes that we care so much about in best ball leagues. Tyler Lockett and Jimmy Graham should also be feeling better and the backfield should be improved, so the offensive pie that Wilson serves up should also get bigger. He adds more value in best ball than his middling ADP indicates.

DoctJo00.name: Josh Doctson
DoctJo00.note: Doctson left practice on Sunday August 6 with a hamstring injury. He is expected to be out through August 17 or 18.

EbroEr00.name: Eric Ebron
EbroEr00.note: Ebron’s lack of touchdowns hurt his weekly ceiling, but his volume still made him a common 15-20 PPR scorer when he was in the lineup. His durability hasn’t been ideal, but drafting him as a TE2 in best ball gives you all the ceiling as Ebron has a chance to absorb a lot of the targets vacated by Anquan Boldin with none of the floor because your TE1 will cover any injury or down weeks.

PerkPa00.name: Paul Perkins
PerkPa00.note: The Giants haven’t had the most robust running game in recent years, and Perkins will have to share with Shane Vereen in the passing game, but if there’s going to be a “hit” in the Giants backfield this year, it will be Perkins. He makes a lot of sense for best ball teams that wait on running back need high season-long ceiling plays in the mid-rounds.

WhitJa04.name: James White
WhitJa04.note: Everyone remembers White’s Super Bowl, but did you know White actually seven PPR double-digit scoring weeks during the regular season and five receiving scores. It is difficult to see his role shrinking after the team signed him to an extension this offseason, so it’s likely he’ll give 5-8 scoring weeks in best ball lineups again at the cheap cost of a 12th or 13th round pick.

SproDa00.name: Darren Sproles
SproDa00.note: Sproles’ fantasy profile is tailored for PPR best ball leagues. He’ll still play a large role in the backfield, especially and occasionally get some red zone looks at the expense of LeGarrette Blount. He should be able to reproduce his four top 15 PPR running back finishes from 2016, making him a bargain and good RB4 or RB5 best ball late pick.

LeexMa01.name: Marqise Lee
LeexMa01.note: Jacksonville Jaguars WR Marqise Lee (leg) reportedly did not suffer a serious leg injury as initially feared after he was carted off during practice Sunday, Aug. 13. He does have a high ankle sprain that could keep sidelined through the season opener.

JoneMa02.name: Marvin Jones
JoneMa02.note: Jones started 2016 like he was going to be a fantasy WR1, in fact he was #1 overall after three weeks. Nagging injuries and poor play brought him down, but the potential he flashed should be enough to take him at an ADP that allows you to slot him as your WR4 or WR5. If Jones disappoints again, he won’t hurt your best ball team, but if he regains his early season form, he could put your roster over the top.

BookDe00.name: Devontae Booker
BookDe00.note: Booker has a wrist injury reported on July 26 and will likely miss 6-8 weeks.

StewAr00.name: ArDarius Stewart
StewAr00.note: Stewart is a fast, physical receiver who can beat cornerbacks deep and block linebackers like an H-Back. He impressed early in Jets camp prior to a surgery during OTAs. He’s in competition for a starting role this month.

RoetBe00.name: Ben Roethlisberger
RoetBe00.note: Best ball is perfect for Roethlisberger because fantasy teams can avoid his road and injury duds while still getting the benefit of his home scoring sprees. Martavis Bryant is back. If Bryant, Ben, Brown, and Bell can stay on the field for most of the season, Roethlisberger should have than enough top 5 scoring weeks to profit on his 9th/10th round cost in drafts.

HurnAl01.name: Allen Hurns
HurnAl01.note: Hurns was a non-factor in the second half of the year, and the emergence of Marqise Lee will combine with a more conservative approach on offense to limit his weekly and season-long ceiling. He’s still useful at his 15th or later round ADP in best ball drafts as the top deep target for the Jaguars.

PerrBr02.name: Breshad Perriman
PerrBr02.note: Perriman has a grade 2 hamstring strain and may miss up to a month, putting his Week 1 availability in question.

SanuMo00.name: Mohamed Sanu
SanuMo00.note: Sanu still had four 15+ point PPR weeks last year despite playing through a shoulder injury and the emergence of Taylor Gabriel. With better health this year, he could build on that, but even if he doesn’t, his 2016 game log would justify the absurdly cheap price it takes to add the #2 receiver in one of the best pass offenses in the NFL.

AndeRo02.name: Robby Anderson
AndeRo02.note: Anderson had a terrific high wire act in the second half of 2016 to produce the big plays that fuel best ball lineups. His value is higher with Bryce Petty at quarterback, but even if Christian Hackenberg wins the job, Anderson is more than worth a very late round pick in best ball leagues with Eric Decker gone to Tennessee.

VereSh00.name: Shane Vereen
VereSh00.note: Vereen had a second triceps surgery this offseason after he re-injured the problem that originally landed him on injured reserve. The team has been cautious with his rehab in the spring, erring on the side of taking it slow. He hopes to be ready for Week 1.

CharJa00.name: Jamaal Charles
CharJa00.note: Charles’ range of outcomes this year is anywhere from not making the team to being the most productive back in the Denver backfield. He has always been a great receiver out of the backfield and CJ Anderson hasn’t had a fully healthy season to date. In best ball drafts you can afford to swing and miss on a late pick or two, so it makes sense to swing for the fences unless you overinvested at the position earlier. Charles is a hail mary that could save a best ball team.

NelsJJ00.name: J.J. Nelson
NelsJJ00.note: Nelson wasn’t fully incorporated into the Cardinals offense until mid-season, but he still produced three 15+ point games. That is enough to make him worth his very late round price tag in best ball leagues. If John Brown can’t regain his past form, Nelson will be one of the best late picks in best ball leagues.

ShepSt00.name: Sterling Shepard
ShepSt00.note: Shepard rolled his ankle in practice on Wednesday August 2. The injury was originally believed to be severe because Shepard was carted off in tears, but it appears that he has avoided any breaks or serious injury.

DaltAn00.name: Andy Dalton
DaltAn00.note: Dalton was a top 13 quarterback in six of eight full games with AJ Green, and he should get Tyler Eifert back this year along with the addition of John Ross and Joe Mixon in the draft. He’ll occasionally run in a score to boost an already high weekly ceiling for a quarterback that usually falls well outside of the top ten drafted. He’s perfect as part of a mid-round 1-2 QB punch in best ball leagues.

CousKi00.name: Kirk Cousins
CousKi00.note: Cousins lost his top two wideouts and offensive coordinator, but he still has a terrific supporting cast and will post a handful of top 3-5 weeks to fuel best ball teams that wait on quarterback. He has been a solid QB1 for the last two years and is going for much less than that in drafts of all types. His willingness to run the ball in himself close in also increases his weekly ceiling.

RivePh00.name: Philip Rivers
RivePh00.note: Rivers downside of two matchup against the Chiefs and Broncos is easily offset in best ball leagues because other quarterbacks on your roster will automatically upgrade your ceiling in those weeks. Rivers’ upside is unknown this year with his top three receivers returning healthy and the addition of #7 overall pick Mike Williams to the wide receiver corps. He’s perfect for a best ball approach that targets two high weekly ceiling options in the QB10-QB15 range.

DaviCo01.name: Corey Davis
DaviCo01.note: Davis reminds Rookie Scouting Portfolio author Matt Waldman of players like Hakeem Nicks and Antonio Bryant because of his smooth route skills and physicality. Davis’ intelligence and work ethic give him the potential to be the Michael Thomas of rookie receivers in 2017. Don’t expect Thomas’ stats, but consider Davis the most likely rookie receiver stand out with starter production. A hamstring injury is limiting his camp momentum.

LewiDi00.name: Dion Lewis
LewiDi00.note: Lewis seemed to fall out of favor after playoff fumbles, but he is still around and looking more like his old self. He is likely to be below James White in the pecking order for touches, but his explosive game and quality surrounding offense make him a good 15th round or later pick if you need to add in a high ceiling weekly option compared to his late-round peers.

GinnTe00.name: Ted Ginn
GinnTe00.note: Ginn already has the ideal profile for a secondary best ball receiver as a deep threat. Being in the Saints pass offense only inflates his weekly ceiling, and he should be the clear #3 target among the wide receivers, which is relatively high rent real estate for a receiver often going well into the second half of best ball drafts.

BennMa00.name: Martellus Bennett
BennMa00.note: Bennett should be able to record 6-8 touchdowns as a top red zone threat for Aaron Rodgers. Perhaps the historical mid to low value at tight end in Green Bay’s offense will keep Bennett from being a consistent fantasy option, but in best ball leagues where you can have 2-3 tight ends, his low points will be smoothed while his high points will enhance your ceiling at a value for his modest mid round price tag.

LockTy00.name: Tyler Lockett
LockTy00.note: Lockett was healthy for only a very small part of 2016 and still produced two 20+ point games. He can easily increase that total if he stays off of the injury report. Lockett’s ADP means that he’s in that range where he doesn’t hurt your team if he is limited for much of the season again, but he can lift your fortunes at a small cost if he makes the next step in 2017.

GabrTa01.name: Taylor Gabriel
GabrTa01.note: Gabriel took a bit to get involved in the Falcons offense after they claimed him right before the season, but once he did, he was a big play machine. His role should be solidified with a full offseason and integration into the offense, and whatever he loses because of ridiculous efficiency per touch last year should be offset by that. He’s a layup in best ball leagues as one of your last wide receiver picks.

TaylTy00.name: Tyrod Taylor
TaylTy00.note: With the return of a healthy Sammy Watkins to fuel the deep passing and the potential for Taylor to add significant rushing yards and a score in any given week, Taylor works as a QB2 to give you a top quarterback scoring ceiling or one-half of a QBBC that should allow to you hang with teams that spent more resources at the position - all at the cost of a pick in the second half of drafts.

MattJo02.name: Jordan Matthews
MattJo02.note: Matthews is week-to-week with a chip fracture in his sternum.

MannEl00.name: Eli Manning
MannEl00.note: Manning was disappointing in just about every way last year, including a season that put him among the bottom dwellers in 20+ and 25+ point games at quarterback, but this year he gained Brandon Marshall and first-round tight end Evan Engram. The risk that he remains a boring weekly option is easy to account for in best ball leagues when you draft another quarterback around the same part of your draft with a higher weekly floor like Philip Rivers or Dak Prescott.

FlacJo00.name: Joe Flacco
FlacJo00.note: Flacco could miss up to 3-6 weeks with a disc issue in his back reported on July 26.

KizeDe00.name: DeShone Kizer
KizeDe00.note: Kizer impressed during his first preseason appearance, demonstrating the strong arm, pocket presence, deep accuracy, and field reading that he often flashed at Notre Dame. Brock Osweiler folded once again under the lights. Look for Kizer to start in Cleveland sooner than later. His physical skills alone should help him become a solid garbage-time option.

TrubMi00.name: Mitchell Trubisky
TrubMi00.note: Rookie quarterbacks sometimes make good late-round darts. Trubisky displayed poise, intermediate accuracy, and mobility in a Bears game plan that moved him around and gave him basic decisions. Mike Glennon, like Brock Osweiler in Cleveland, looked bad.

ThomJu00.name: Julius Thomas
ThomJu00.note: Thomas is unlikely to return to true fantasy relevance this year, but he can help best ball teams that need a third tight end to potentially fill gaps left by a weak top two choices at the position. He scored nine times in 21 games with the Jaguars, and the last time we saw Thomas with Miami head coach Adam Gase, he was a red zone wonder in Denver. He’ll find the end zone enough to make his 13th/14th round price reasonable if you feel forced to go with three tight ends.

FleeCo00.name: Coby Fleener
FleeCo00.note: Fleener was a disaster in redraft leagues last year, but he did provide two games over 20 points, something only 13 other tight ends did in 2016, and important in best ball leagues. There’s room for growth with another year in the offense under his belt, but even if Fleener doesn’t improve, he’ll add to your bottom line as a third tight end as long as he does what he did last year.

BratCa01.name: Cameron Brate
BratCa01.note: Brate was tied for third in production of 15+ point games among tight ends last year, but he is going well outside of the TE1 ranks and even after rookie and fellow Buc tight end OJ Howard. Brate’s chemistry with Jameis Winston in the red zone won’t go away. He’s low-hanging fruit as a fine TE2 or bonus big week TE3 in best ball drafts.

SefeAu01.name: Austin Seferian-Jenkins
SefeAu01.note: Austin Seferian-Jenkins has been suspended two games for violating the NFL’s substance abuse drug policy. This means he will miss Weeks 1-2 of the 2017 season.

GateAn00.name: Antonio Gates
GateAn00.note: Gates snaps will likely go down this year, but his targets could stay mostly intact, as he’ll be on the field for passing down and red zone situations to use his receiving ability and chemistry with Philip Rivers. That makes him a fine best ball pick as a third tight end to add weekly ceiling to a lackluster duo, or even a second tight end to fill in a bye and provide injury insurance for a safe top TE1 like Travis Kelce or Greg Olsen.

KamaAl00.name: Alvin Kamara
KamaAl00.note: Kamara has landed in the receiving role for a team that is always among the leaders in running back targets. His usage could be inconsistent week to week, but in best ball leagues, you’ll have plenty of other options to cover those weeks while still getting the boost from the weeks that the Saints make Kamara one of their main matchups to exploit. Kamara also offers injury upside if Mark Ingram or Adrian Peterson miss time.

FullWi00.name: Will Fuller
FullWi00.note: Fuller was a WR1 after four weeks and then injuries and the Texans putrid passing game dragged him down to being barely rosterable in most leagues for the rest of the season. That could change this year with the introduction of Deshaun Watson at quarterback. Fuller’s deep speed and the promise of a functional pass offense makes him an excellent hail mary in best ball leagues in the 13th round or later.

KuppCo00.name: Cooper Kupp
KuppCo00.note: The Sammy Watkins trade may have put a dent in the hype machine for Kupp, but Kupp will most likely play in the slot more often than outside. He has been praised for his command of the offense and it wouldn’t be surprising if he earns the slot role ahead of Tavon Austin and still earns a high target volume that most are writing off due to Watkins.

EngrEv00.name: Evan Engram
EngrEv00.note: Engram isn’t the starter, but he’ll likely earn a lot of playing time as a slot receiver and H-Back. He has performed well in camp and his size-speed combination has been a real mismatch for linebackers and safeties. Think of him more as a high-end slot receiver earning easy matchups and not as a rookie tight end.

ThomCh01.name: Chris Thompson
ThomCh01.note: Thompson isn’t going to add much to a best ball roster’s weekly ceiling, but he could save the bacon of teams that go lean and mean at running back. His steady receiving back role provides a solid floor for bye weeks and injuries and the very late round price is right for cheap points at running back.

RossJo00.name: John Ross
RossJo00.note: Ross has the classic deep ball game to move the needle in best ball leagues. He can put up a top 20 wide receiver week on one play, and should be able to do that at least a few times this year if he gets and stays healthy, assuming Andy Dalton does too. That makes ideal for a choice as one of your later wide receivers in the best ball format.

StilKe00.name: Kenny Stills
StilKe00.note: Perhaps fantasy players see DeVante Parker’s breakout coming and expect Stills to shrink into the background, but the 20 million guaranteed dollars he got in the offseason indicate otherwise. Even if his snaps and targets suffer a bit due to a Parker breakout, Stills should still get enough deep targets and conversions to make him easily worth the cost as one of your last wide receivers in a best ball draft.

RichPa02.name: Paul Richardson
RichPa02.note: Richardson suffered a sprained AC joint in the preseason opener and will "out a bit" according to the team.

BurkRe00.name: Rex Burkhead
BurkRe00.note: Before the Patriots signed RFA Mike Gillislee to an offer sheet and the Bills let him walk, Burkhead looked like he might be the most valuable fantasy back in New England. He should still contribute some scoring weeks with his hands out of the backfield and sense of urgency running inside, and with an injury or two to his competitors for touches, do even more. He’s available late in best ball drafts and could end up being a brilliant pick if you need a late hail mary.

SmitTo02.name: Torrey Smith
SmitTo02.note: There is a non-zero risk that Smith gets released because he’s only due $500,000 guaranteed, but as long as he makes the Eagles final roster, Smith should be the top deep threat for Carson Wentz. Even if he only reels in two or three long scores, those plays alone will make him worth the very late pick he costs in best ball drafts. If he has a true bounceback (it’s not impossible at 28), he’ll be one of the steals of your best ball draft.

McFaDa00.name: Darren McFadden
McFaDa00.note: The Cowboys chose to re-sign McFadden even though they still had Alfred Morris under contract. He should be the clear backup to Ezekiel Elliott and would inherit the pilot seat to the best running game in the league if Elliott goes down.

WatsBe00.name: Ben Watson
WatsBe00.note: A Pro-Bowl performer with the Saints two years ago, the aging veteran signed a lucrative free agent deal last year before tearing his Achilles in camp. Watson is practicing without restriction and the Ravens didn’t add another veteran to the mix when Dennis Pitta suffered what is likely a career-ending injury.

AustTa00.name: Tavon Austin
AustTa00.note: Austin had as many 15+ point games (5) as Kenny Britt in the same terrible Rams pass offense last year. If Sean McVay and company make them incrementally better in the play design and play-calling department, Austin’s big game/big play total could increase, but even if he doesn’t, his ADP is screaming value in best ball leagues.

RichJa00.name: Jalen Richard
RichJa00.note: Richard was an excellent yards-after-contact producer last year and he’s a more physical runner to DeAndre Washington, a more touted prospect who has improved this year in camp but is still in a tight competition for the role of Marshawn Lynch’s backup.

WillMi06.name: Mike Williams
WillMi06.note: Williams missed OTAs with a "mild" disc herniation in his back, but there is some concern that he will need season-ending surgery. He has started camp on the PUP list and the team has announced that he will not practice in camp.

PeakCh00.name: Charone Peake
PeakCh00.note: Peake lacks great speed, but he has build-up speed and a physical style. He tracks the ball well and with a full year in the organization, he’s one of the favorites to start on a team that could be in garbage-time mode early and often.

AlleDw00.name: Dwayne Allen
AlleDw00.note: Allen has always been a fantasy tease, but expectations have adjusted low enough now that his injury-prone nature is tolerable at a late-round cost in best ball leagues. He’ll probably score 4-6 times if he can play in at least thirteen games, as he has in four out of five years, and if Rob Gronkowski goes down, he might make your best ball at tight end.

GollKe00.name: Kenny Golladay
GollKe00.note: The rookie has impressed throughout training camp as a physical player with good ball-tracking skill. He did the same during his preseason debut with two touchdowns against the Colts.

RogeCh02.name: Chester Rogers
RogeCh02.note: Rogers impressed last year as a rookie and he has a shot of unseating Phillip Dorsett for his spot in the rotation. Rogers has downfield speed, but he has shown more than Dorsett as a route runner.

ZennZa00.name: Zach Zenner
ZennZa00.note: Zenner has enough athletic ability and all-around skill to become the lead back in the Lions offense if called upon.

HogaCh00.name: Chris Hogan
HogaCh00.note: The addition of Brandin Cooks made fantasy football players forget about Hogan, but you can be certain Tom Brady hasn’t. Hogan scored four times last year and had another 100-yard receiving game. The Patriots passing game is crowded, but Hogan should be able to give you 4-5 scoring weeks and a very late round pick price again this year with the gameplan of the week nature of the Patriots offense.

SwooEr00.name: Erik Swoope
SwooEr00.note: Swoope is a last-round pick in best ball drafts, but he offers a high season-long and weekly ceiling for a minuscule cost. He has big play ability, his role should grow with the trade of Dwayne Allen, and Swoope also happens to play with Andrew Luck.

SamuCu00.name: Curtis Samuel
SamuCu00.note: At the very least, Samuel should pick up the slack left by the loss of Ted Ginn in the vertical passing game, which should translate to 3-5 scoring weeks when he can reel in the deep ball. If Samuel can make some big plays with run after catch or otherwise find other ways to get involved, he could be a nice surprise beyond his obvious best ball value.

SimsDi00.name: Dion Sims
SimsDi00.note: Rookie Adam Shaheen will be the player many analysts call for if Zach Miller gets hurt again, but Sims is the superior blocker and more experienced receiver with route adjustments at the NFL level. Sims is a solid two-way option who may eventually give way to Shaheen but will get the first shot this year and has the talent to thrive.

RodgJa00.name: Jacquizz Rodgers
RodgJa00.note: Rodgers is worth drafting late in best ball leagues simply to get the benefit of his likely three starts to begin the season while Doug Martin is suspended. Beyond that, he has Martin injury upside and the chance for a big game/play or two as a change of pace back.

MarsJa00.name: Jalin Marshall
MarsJa00.note: Marshall is suspended for the first four games of the 2017 season for a violation of the league policy on performance-enhancing drugs.

WillJo02.name: Jonathan Williams
WillJo02.note: When the Bills didn’t match the Patriots offer sheet to RFA back Mike Gillislee, the 2016 fifth-round pick was thrust into the clear backup role. He’s a potential three-down back who could have went higher in the draft, but missed his senior season with a foot injury. The Bills have no other backups of his caliber and he would take over a strong running game if LeSean McCoy goes down.

BenjTr00.name: Travis Benjamin
BenjTr00.note: Benjamin is a classic deep threat who shouldn’t be falling to the end of best ball drafts. He played through an injury during the second half of the season and even if rookie Mike Williams secures a big role, Benjamin is still has the best vertical speed in this wide receiver group and should contribute at least a few big play scores to reward those who pay the minimal ticket price for his best ball services.

ConnJa00.name: James Conner
ConnJa00.note: Le’Veon Bell is yet to make it through a season healthy. DeAngelo Williams was a league winner when Bell went down. The Steelers liked Conner enough to take him on the second day of the draft, which should make him the clear backup to Bell this year. If Bell goes down midseason, Conner could push fantasy teams of all types over the top, but this potential is especially enticing for best ball rosters that have a solid 3-4 running backs of high floor options and need a high ceiling option.

HollMa00.name: Mack Hollins
HollMa00.note: Drafted in part for his special teams prowess, Hollins was an underrated receiver at North Carolina. Built a bit like Miles Austin, he’s a strong receiver with the quickness and fluidity to win the ball downfield and make plays after the catch. He’s a consistent performer in training camp and might be part of the reason that Jordan Matthews was expendable.

SmitJu00.name: JuJu Smith-Schuster
SmitJu00.note: Smith-Schuster suffered a concussion in the preseason opener, but returned to practice the following Monday.

GodwCh00.name: Chris Godwin
GodwCh00.note: Mike Evans, Jameis Winston, DeSean Jackson, Ryan Fitzpatrcik, Vernon Hargreaves, and Dirk Koetter have all complimented Godwin for learning the offense faster than most. Godwin has made physical, acrobatic plays on a consistent basis and could earn time as the No. 3 option this year.

ForeDO00.name: DOnta Foreman
ForeDO00.note: Foreman’s size, burst, and decision-making maturity make him a good late-round dart who could thrive if Lamar Miller gets hurt. He’ll need to prove he can pass protect and maintain ball security. His pass pro grades were strong according to Pro Football Focus, but his technique flaws have been an issue in camp, which Matt Waldman’s Rookie Scouting Portfolio critiqued in April.

KendLa00.name: Lance Kendricks
KendLa00.note: A Martellus Bennett injury could thrust the versatile Kendricks into the lineup. He’s a smart player who’s fantasy value could be greater with a quarterback like Rodgers, because of his reliability.

PerrDe99.name: Denzel Perryman
PerrDe99.note: Perryman will miss 8-10 weeks after ankle surgery. The injury occurred on Sunday August 13 in the preseason opener.

MitcMa01.name: Malcolm Mitchell
MitcMa01.note: Mitchell flashed as a big-play threat in the Patriots offense as a rookie. If injury strikes, Mitchell could become a central figure in the Patriots plays.

OlivBr02.name: Branden Oliver
OlivBr02.note: His burst is back, according to reporters who have observed Oliver’s return to camp after an Achilles’ injury. He’s the smartest back on the roster when it comes to the overall duties of the position.

WestDe00.name: Dede Westbrook
WestDe00.note: Westbrook has a lot of traits that are similar to T.Y. Hilton. He’s performing in training camp and if he proves he can defeat press coverage, his upside could rise dramatically with an injury to one of the three starters.

MahoPa00.name: Patrick Mahomes II
MahoPa00.note: Mahomes has a rare arm, great creativity, and good mobility in the pocket. Travis Kelce says Mahomes has also learned the offense faster than he did. Strong camp and preseason performances could earn him the No. 2 role. If it does, he could have great upside because he’s not afraid to make tight-window throws and downfield shots that Alex Smith shies from.

SwitRy00.name: Ryan Switzer
SwitRy00.note: Quicker and a better runner than Cole Beasley, Switzer is slated to earn time on the field even with Beasley as the starter. Beasley is the present, but Switzer’s talent as a route runner and ball carrier is the future. It could be immediate with a Beasley injury.

BucaDe99.name: Deone Bucannon
BucaDe99.note: Bucannon had ankle surgery in May. The team hopes he will be ready for Week 1, but he is questionable for the open of the season and could land on the reserve/PUP list, sidelining him for at least the first six games of the season.

RobiDe01.name: Demarcus Robinson
RobiDe01.note: Tall, athletic and physical, Robinson has earned time in the starting rotation this summer and helped make Jeremy Maclin expendable. His value could rise significantly with an injury or Patrick Mahomes’ insertion into the lineup.

RayxSh99.name: Shane Ray
RayxSh99.note: Ray had surgery on his wrist on Saturday July 29 and will be out 6-8 weeks.

FloyMi00.name: Michael Floyd
FloyMi00.note: Floyd will be suspended for the first four games of the 2017 season under the league policy on substance abuse.

RandDa99.name: Damarious Randall
RandDa99.note: Randall suffered a concussion in the first preseason game.

ThomEa99.name: Earl Thomas
ThomEa99.note: Thomas suffered a broken tibia in December 2016, but he and head coach Pete Carroll expect him to be ready for the 2017 season opener. Thomas pronounced himself at 80 percent in mid-June.

GathRi00.name: Rico Gathers
GathRi00.note: Gathers has impressed the entire offseason as a downfield receiver. He’s winning matchups with his speed and size, and he’s finishing plays with his hand-eye coordination. If Jason Witten gets hurt, Gathers has flashed the talent to become an instant fantasy starter.

CollJa98.name: Jalen Collins
CollJa98.note: Collins has been suspended for ten games for violating the league policy on performance-enhancing drugs

GeatCl98.name: Clayton Geathers
GeatCl98.note: Geathers had neck surgery in March and is uncertain for Week 1. He is expected to begin the season on the PUP list.

WaynTr99.name: Trae Waynes
WaynTr99.note: Waynes suffered a shoulder injury in the first preseason game, but the team does not think it is serious.

SmitMa97.name: Malcolm Smith
SmitMa97.note: Smith is out for the season with a chest injury.

JoneAd99.name: Adam Jones
JoneAd99.note: Jones is suspended for one game for violating the league’s personal conduct policy.

BreaDe99.name: Delvin Breaux
BreaDe99.note: New Orleans Saints CB Delvin Breaux (leg) had an X-ray on his injured left leg Monday, Aug. 14, according to head coach Sean Payton. He’ll be out 4-6 weeks with a broken fibula.

JohnCh04.name: Chris Johnson
JohnCh04.note: We all know Chris Johnson, but many don’t realize that he’s back with the Cardinals. Kerwynn Williams is earning preseason carries which also may confuse the issue for fantasy owners who may not realize that Johnson probably won’t see looks until the preseason tune-up. If David Johnson gets hurt, look for Chris to thrive.

LangKe98.name: Kendall Langford
LangKe98.note: Langford is starting camp on the PUP because of knee issue, but the team said he should be ready for the regular season.

HydeKe99.name: Kerry Hyder
HydeKe99.note: Hyder is out for the season with an achilles injury.

IlokGe99.name: George Iloka
IlokGe99.note: Iloka suffered a strained knee on July 30 and will be sidelined 3-4 weeks.

ButtJa00.name: Jake Butt
ButtJa00.note: Butt tore an ACL in the Orange Bowl. He has said he could be cleared to return anywhere from mid-July to mid-October. He will most likely start the season on the PUP list.

SmitRo06.name: Rod Smith
SmitRo06.note: Smith has excellent size and flexibility. He’s quick enough to take the edge as a perimeter runner, but he’s a true interior, north-south runner. Smith has performed well enough in camp to threaten Alfred Morris’ job. The former top prospect at Ohio State was a UDFA because Urban Meyer kicked him off the team for repeated disciplinary issues.

MoorDa98.name: Damontre Moore
MoorDa98.note: Moore has been suspended two games for violating the league’s substance abuse policy.

WillKe04.name: Kerwynn Williams
WillKe04.note: Despite re-signing Chris Johnson, Williams is worth keeping an eye on because of his play and Johnson’s age. Williams has burst to the edge, runs intelligently up the middle, and he can catch the ball. Bruce Arians trusts Williams and he’s producing at a confident level throughout training camp.

McDoMa99.name: Malik McDowell
McDoMa99.note: McDowell did not report to camp after a serious traffic accident in mid-July. There were no details on his condition or injuries from the accident.

McKiTa99.name: Takkarist McKinley
McKiTa99.note: McKinley underwent shoulder surgery on March 3 to return a torn labrum and glenoid fracture. He could miss up to six months. The Falcons have not put a timetable on his return. The team is optimistic that he will be ready for training camp, but head Dan Quinn was still unsure if that would happen in mid-June.

JoneAa00.name: Aaron Jones
JoneAa00.note: If Ty Montgomery or Jamaal Williams get hurt, Jones could figure prominently in the backfield. He’s quick and savvy between the tackles and he has a great pair of hands in the receiving game.

McDoT.99.name: T.J. McDonald
McDoT.99.note: McDonald has been suspended for the first eight games of the 2017 season for violating the league substance abuse rules.

NiklTr01.name: Troy Niklas
NiklTr01.note: An unlikely upside candidate in an offense that hasn’t targeted the tight end as a priority in its scheme, Niklas’ numerous injuries have been part of the reason. However, he’s a fluid perimeter option with skill above the rim when healthy. He’s healthy and having a solid training camp.

MurpTr99.name: Trent Murphy
MurpTr99.note: Murphy has a torn ACL and will miss the 2017 season.

McMiRa99.name: Raekwon McMillan
McMiRa99.note: The Dolphins fear McMillan suffered a torn ACL in the first preseason game.

BrowMa03.name: Malcolm Brown
BrowMa03.note: Brown is a big, bruising runner with good burst and capable hands in the passing game. The former five-star recruit from Texas is the No. 2 option on the Rams depth chart that has improved its offensive line. Eric Dickerson and Marshall Faulk were both impressed with Brown last year, and he has the skills to surprise if Todd Gurley gets hurt.

HendDe01.name: DeAngelo Henderson
HendDe01.note: Henderson has a Maurice Jones-Drew build. He’s comfortable running from gap schemes in the shotgun, which Denver will do more of this year. He has impressed enough this summer to earn first-team reps because he has hit creases confidently and created well in space. He could surprise if C.J. Anderson and/or Devontae Booker falter.

IrviDa99.name: David Irving
IrviDa99.note: Irving is facing a four-game suspension for performance-enhancing drug usage.

McPhPe99.name: Pernell McPhee
McPhPe99.note: McPhee underwent arthroscopic surgery on his right knee on Friday, July 28. The team is characterizing it as a "clean up", but there is no timetable for his return.

FairNi99.name: Nick Fairley
FairNi99.note: New Orleans Saints DT Nick Fairley (heart) will not play in 2017 due to his heart condition. His career is also in jeopardy.

HendCa00.name: Carlos Henderson
HendCa00.note: Henderson had mid-August thumb surgery. The team said he is day-to-day.

AlliGe00.name: Geronimo Allison
AlliGe00.note: Allison has earned some positive comparisons to Marques Colston. After some impressive rookie moments in the lineup, he could build on that production in a bigger way if called upon.

MorgDa00.name: David Morgan
MorgDa00.note: A physical, strong blocker and extremely quick, Morgan could shock as a fluid, sure-handed receiver for Sam Bradford if Kyle Rudolph gets hurt.

CarrLe00.name: Leonte Carroo
CarrLe00.note: He couldn’t stay on the field last year because Adam Gase asked Carroo to learn all three wide receiver positions. Gase took responsibility for that and Carroo arrived in-shape and more prepared. Carroo is making more plays as the summer has progressed.

MoorKe01.name: Kellen Moore
MoorKe01.note: If Dak Prescott gets hurt, Moore has developed enough arm strength to finally hang in the NFL. His true strength is reading defenses. With the Cowboys surrounding talent, any smart decision-maker at quarterback merits your attention.

HundBr00.name: Brett Hundley
HundBr00.note: Teams inquired about Hundley during the 2017 NFL Draft. He’s a mobile, strong-armed prospect with a better mental processor and pocket presence than credited pre-draft. He surprised and impressed the Packers with these skills as a rookie and has improved each year behind the scenes. He could be a QB1 in this offense if Rodgers gets hurt.

CoatSa00.name: Sammie Coates
CoatSa00.note: Coates had a knee scope in mid-July and will be out at least through mid-August and start camp on the PUP list.

DaviJu00.name: Justin Davis
DaviJu00.note: The former USC tailback has excellent quickness and finishes runs hard. He’s a fine zone runner who had a tall skinny frame. Matt Waldman’s Rookie Scouting Portfolio touted Davis as a long-term project who looked like he could add 12-20 pounds and have a pro career that exceeds his college performances. Davis has impressed in camp and he has added significant muscle.

WashDw00.name: Dwayne Washington
WashDw00.note: Washington has Adrian Peterson’s physical dimensions, speed, and burst. He’s also powerful like Peterson. The differences are vision, ball security, and overall decision-making. Washington has had big-time flashes. If he puts it together, he could be a gem.
